[required] Title: Fwd: RM Integris URL Change - Update
Description:
Forwarded message ---------
From: rmintegris <rmintegris@rm.com>
Date: Wed, 24 May 2023 at 12:03
Subject: RM Integris URL Change - Update
To: rmintegris <rmintegris@rm.com>


Dear Customer,



Further to our previous communication regarding the planned change to the
Integris URL (website address), we are pleased to confirm that the change
is scheduled to take place this coming weekend and will be in place by *7pm
Sunday 28th May 2023. *



The following notifications were published yesterday on both Integris
messages and our status page.  For further information please refer to the
help article referenced in the post below.



*Maintenance window* – *Integris Downtime*

The following maintenance window will be required resulting in Integris
being unavailable between *4.30am Saturday 27th May – 7pm Sunday 28th May.*

If your school has setup its own DataShare link (API) to pull data into a
bespoke database that your school has setup, please also refrain from
pulling API data during this maintenance window.



*Date of planned change to the Integris URL*

The Integris URL is planned to change this coming weekend, so from *7pm on
Sunday, 28th May* you will need to use the new Integris URL.

Please refer to the following help page for action you may need to take and
for further information:
https://help.rmintegris.com/integris-url-is-changing

If there are any changes to this date, we will advise you accordingly.



*What if I access Integris from RM Unify?*

If you use either one of the ready-made Integris app tiles or if your
school has created one of their own link tiles to access and log in to
Integris, either way our team will be updating the Integris URL for you.
Please refer to our help page for further information:
https://help.rmintegris.com/integris-url-is-changing



*What will happen if I forget to use the new URL?*

If you use the old URL a page will appear advising you of the change,
together with a link to the new URL whilst also reminding the user to
update their shortcut or bookmark.



*Who do I contact if I need help?*
If you have any queries or need further assistance, please contact your
usual RM Integris Support Partner in the first instance.



With best wishes





*SESL MIS Team*

---------- Forwarded message ---------
From: Accessit Library <info@accessitlibrary.co.uk>
Date: Wed, 24 May 2023 at 10:39
Subject: Important - Cloud Server Changes Beginning June 3rd
To: Karen <k.bramhill@bhs.hlt.academy>


Simple changes are required, please read here to find out more...
*Important Info For All Cloud Based Customers*
Dear Karen,

We want to ensure you have the best possible experience with Accessit. As
part of our commitment to providing you with top-quality service, we are
transitioning to a new state-of-the-art data center. This means that all
our current UK customers will be migrated to this new infrastructure.

*What does this mean for you?*

This transition will mean improved performance and stability of our
services. During the weekend of* June 3rd and 4th, there may be minor
service disruptions*. We will make every effort to keep these disruptions
to a minimum.

The *complete domain changeover will take place on June 18th*. This means
you have ample time to apply the necessary changes. However, to ensure a
smooth transition, we need your cooperation.

*What do you need to do?*

Update your firewall rules: Please contact your IT technicians and request
them to allow an outbound connection to the following details:


*IP Address: 149.137.219.247 TCP Port: 2731*

Do note that some customers will need to update the configuration file in
their locally installed application folder to connect to the new server. We
can either email you the updated file or our Tech Support team can modify
the existing file directly after June 4th. No other changes to your current
workflow will be required.
If you have any questions or require assistance, *please don't hesitate to
contact our support team* at support@accessitlibrary.com.

We appreciate your understanding and patience during this transitional
phase. We are confident that this move will significantly improve your
overall experience with Accessit.

Kind regards,
*The Accessit Team*

The provider of Integris, RM, recently contacted all school users about
changes within their company.  It’s come to our attention that this email
has worried some schools about the longevity of Integris.

   - You have a contract with RM for your Integris licence
   - CYC MIS provide you with support in using Integris



*To reassure and clarify*, we have been in touch with RM:

   - Integris is still your management information system
   - There are *no *imminent plans for Integris to be removed from the
   market.  RM have assured us that they are as committed to supporting
   schools and partners in their new home.



What do you need to do:

   - RM have recently sold some elements of the business and changed the
   name of the arm of the business that includes Integris.  Due to this, an
   email asking schools to update their invoicing details has been
   distributed.  However, if you receive finance support through CYC,
   invoicing details have been updated accordingly.

   this new website is allowed on your network so that when the address

There are checks and steps needed to enable your school to be Fit for Next

*Checklist – Technician*

   - Latest version of SIMS .net
   - Install the latest SIMS Data Exchange Patch (available in SOLUS)
   - SIMS Services Manager is active and configured correctly

   - SIMS Usage Package is installed and switched on
   - SIMS Data Exchange Service Package is installed

Subject: Attention: All RM Integris Users
To:


Good morning,



*For the attention of all customers who access either Live or Archive
Integris MIS *You will already be aware of the move for RM Integris to SESL
(Schools Educational Services Ltd) and as part of this move, we will be
required to change the web address in which you access Integris in the
coming weeks. This applies to whether you access either a Live or Archive
copy of Integris.

As you will be aware we have recently updated Integris to v3.178
https://help.rmintegris.com/v3.178 where we have added an in-app message
that informs you of the new Integris URL for your school when accessing
Integris directly via a web browser bookmark/shortcut.  Importantly it also
advises you to arrange with your technical support whitelisting of the new
domain names.   If accessing Integris through RM Unify (RM Integris Plus)
then RM Unify will handle the change of URL and bookmarks and shortcuts
will not need to be changed, however the new domains should still be
whitelisted to prevent access issues.



*Whitelisting New Domain Names *

Within a MAT, local authority, or school you will likely have some sort of
network security solution such as a firewall which protects an
establishment from unwanted traffic and to block malware.  These rules also
prevent users within the network from accessing certain websites and
programs to protect staff and pupils.  As we are changing the website
address of Integris, the firewall may also need to be updated, and to
whitelist the new Integris domain name to prevent it from getting blocked.
A typical firewall uses a whitelist policy where certain websites you trust
are added to prevent them from getting blocked.  Please consult with your
technical teams to ensure your firewall or any other similar security
system you may have in place have the following domains added to the
whitelist.  Sometimes the whitelist is managed centrally by a local
authority, MAT or managed service.  The firewall whitelist should be
updated in either case of accessing Integris through a direct URL or
through RM Unify.



This should be in place *by Friday 26th May* at the latest and can be added
sooner.   Any reference to existing Integris whitelist entries should
remain in place for now.



The domain names to be added to the whitelist are as follows:

*.integris-education.com

*.sesl-education.com



*What will happen if I forget to use the new URL?*

If you use the old URL a page will appear advising you of the change,
together with a link to the new URL whilst also reminding the user to
update their shortcut or bookmark.



*Who do I contact if I need help?*
If you have any queries or need further assistance, please contact your
usual RM Integris Support Partner in the first instance.



With best wishes





*SESL MIS Team*

From: rmintegris <rmintegris@rm.com>
Date: Thu, 18 May 2023 at 09:23
Subject: Attention: All RM Integris Users
To:


Good morning,



*For the attention of all customers who access either Live or Archive
Integris MIS *You will already be aware of the move for RM Integris to SESL
(Schools Educational Services Ltd) and as part of this move, we will be
required to change the web address in which you access Integris in the
coming weeks. This applies to whether you access either a Live or Archive
copy of Integris.

As you will be aware we have recently updated Integris to v3.178
https://help.rmintegris.com/v3.178 where we have added an in-app message
that informs you of the new Integris URL for your school when accessing
Integris directly via a web browser bookmark/shortcut.  Importantly it also
advises you to arrange with your technical support whitelisting of the new
domain names.   If accessing Integris through RM Unify (RM Integris Plus)
then RM Unify will handle the change of URL and bookmarks and shortcuts
will not need to be changed, however the new domains should still be
whitelisted to prevent access issues.



*Whitelisting New Domain Names *

Within a MAT, local authority, or school you will likely have some sort of
network security solution such as a firewall which protects an
establishment from unwanted traffic and to block malware.  These rules also
prevent users within the network from accessing certain websites and
programs to protect staff and pupils.  As we are changing the website
address of Integris, the firewall may also need to be updated, and to
whitelist the new Integris domain name to prevent it from getting blocked.
A typical firewall uses a whitelist policy where certain websites you trust
are added to prevent them from getting blocked.  Please consult with your
technical teams to ensure your firewall or any other similar security
system you may have in place have the following domains added to the
whitelist.  Sometimes the whitelist is managed centrally by a local
authority, MAT or managed service.  The firewall whitelist should be
updated in either case of accessing Integris through a direct URL or
through RM Unify.



This should be in place *by Friday 26th May* at the latest and can be added
sooner.   Any reference to existing Integris whitelist entries should
remain in place for now.



The domain names to be added to the whitelist are as follows:

*.integris-education.com

*.sesl-education.com



*What will happen if I forget to use the new URL?*

If you use the old URL a page will appear advising you of the change,
together with a link to the new URL whilst also reminding the user to
update their shortcut or bookmark.



*Who do I contact if I need help?*
If you have any queries or need further assistance, please contact your
usual RM Integris Support Partner in the first instance.



With best wishes





*SESL MIS Team*

From: rmintegris <rmintegris@rm.com>
Sent: 18 May 2023 9:19 AM
Subject: Attention: All RM Integris Users


This email originated from outside of the organisation. Do not click links or open attachments unless you recognise the sender and know the content is safe.

Good morning,

For the attention of all customers who access either Live or Archive Integris MIS

You will already be aware of the move for RM Integris to SESL (Schools Educational Services Ltd) and as part of this move, we will be required to change the web address in which you access Integris in the coming weeks. This applies to whether you access either a Live or Archive copy of Integris.

As you will be aware we have recently updated Integris to v3.178  https://help.rmintegris.com/v3.178 where we have added an in-app message that informs you of the new Integris URL for your school when accessing Integris directly via a web browser bookmark/shortcut.  Importantly it also advises you to arrange with your technical support whitelisting of the new domain names.   If accessing Integris through RM Unify (RM Integris Plus) then RM Unify will handle the change of URL and bookmarks and shortcuts will not need to be changed, however the new domains should still be whitelisted to prevent access issues.



Whitelisting New Domain Names

Within a MAT, local authority, or school you will likely have some sort of network security solution such as a firewall which protects an establishment from unwanted traffic and to block malware.  These rules also prevent users within the network from accessing certain websites and programs to protect staff and pupils.  As we are changing the website address of Integris, the firewall may also need to be updated, and to whitelist the new Integris domain name to prevent it from getting blocked.  A typical firewall uses a whitelist policy where certain websites you trust are added to prevent them from getting blocked.  Please consult with your technical teams to ensure your firewall or any other similar security system you may have in place have the following domains added to the whitelist.  Sometimes the whitelist is managed centrally by a local authority, MAT or managed service.  The firewall whitelist should be updated in either case of accessing Integris through a direct URL or through RM Unify.



This should be in place by Friday 26th May at the latest and can be added sooner.   Any reference to existing Integris whitelist entries should remain in place for now.



The domain names to be added to the whitelist are as follows:

*.integris-education.com

*.sesl-education.com



What will happen if I forget to use the new URL?

If you use the old URL a page will appear advising you of the change, together with a link to the new URL whilst also reminding the user to update their shortcut or bookmark.



Who do I contact if I need help?
If you have any queries or need further assistance, please contact your usual RM Integris Support Partner in the first instance.



With best wishes





SESL MIS Team

I have raised this question before, however now want to address this again
as the impact is greater.

At present I am unable to reset passwords at any level.

What this results in is that students having to leave the lesson and get
their password reset. This results in them losing learning time and
potentially causing behavioural issues around school. I imagine some also
take advantage of this, as a teacher I have no way of knowing.

This loss of time is compounded if the person who can reset the passwords
is unavailable, as they are busy elsewhere. I imagine that will always be a
potential risk.

An example of how much this impacts is that today I wanted to complete an
assessed piece of work, using PC’s and CAD during lesson 4. I have had 7
students who need passwords resetting for either PC or Google. They could
not complete their CAD assessment this lesson and has also resulted in them
starting to become frustrated and some negative behavioural issues, due to
their frustration.

In addition to the issue of the passwords there are more and more software
updates being requested and this then causes the PC to re-boot after
logging in, resulting in more delays and more time being wasted. Is it
possible to schedule the updates overnight?

Can we please look at a more effective system, in terms of reducing the
loss to learning? I understand that since the “incident” we need more
complex password systems; however at present some students also struggle to
cope with the complexity of the new system. They are issued a new password
and then once logged in then have to renew that password; some struggle to
do this as they are not not aware of the complexity of the password
required. Others just forget the password. They also now have two passwords
to remember; one for the PC and one for Google Classroom.

I have worked in several schools and two in this trust, at all schools I as
a basic teacher have had password control access, to reset a password of a
student. I have taught for 26 years and for many of those delivered IT and
Computer Science, so I am aware of the need of security protocols. However
the current system is detrimental to making good progress for a number of
students when trying to use IT to enhance learning.

Thank you

Ed

[required] Title: Password problems, updates and lost time in learning
Description:
I have raised this question before, however now want to address this again
as the impact is greater.

At present I am unable to reset passwords at any level.

What this results in is that students having to leave the lesson and get
their password reset. This results in them losing learning time and
potentially causing behavioural issues around school. I imagine some also
take advantage of this, as a teacher I have no way of knowing.

This loss of time is compounded if the person who can reset the passwords
is unavailable, as they are busy elsewhere. I imagine that will always be a
potential risk.

An example of how much this impacts is that today I wanted to complete an
assessed piece of work, using PC’s and CAD during lesson 4. I have had 7
students who need passwords resetting for either PC or Google. They could
not complete their CAD assessment this lesson and has also resulted in them
starting to become frustrated and some negative behavioural issues, due to
their frustration.

In addition to the issue of the passwords there are more and more software
updates being requested and this then causes the PC to re-boot after
logging in, resulting in more delays and more time being wasted. Is it
possible to schedule the updates overnight?

Can we please look at a more effective system, in terms of reducing the
loss to learning? I understand that since the “incident” we need more
complex password systems; however at present some students also struggle to
cope with the complexity of the new system. They are issued a new password
and then once logged in then have to renew that password; some struggle to
do this as they are not not aware of the complexity of the password
required. Others just forget the password. They also now have two passwords
to remember; one for the PC and one for Google Classroom.

I have worked in several schools and two in this trust, at all schools I as
a basic teacher have had password control access, to reset a password of a
student. I have taught for 26 years and for many of those delivered IT and
Computer Science, so I am aware of the need of security protocols. However
the current system is detrimental to making good progress for a number of
students when trying to use IT to enhance learning.

Thank you

Ed

Subject: InVentry System Refresh - Woodlesford Primary School | CRM:03292235


Hi Jackie

Thank you for returning your system refresh documentation.

Our next available date for your refresh is 26/05/2023. I have reserved this date for you until close of business Tuesday (16/05/2023). If you could confirm suitability as soon as possible, it would be greatly appreciated. If we haven’t received confirmation by this date, the reservation will be removed and we will need to arrange a new date.

We do require your IT support technician to assist the engineer with network ports/network IP addresses, testing the backup, testing the MIS, installing Anti-Virus and adding the InVentry admin software to the various computers.

The new version of the software will require a backup location, for the InVentry database, that will be hosted from the InVentry touchscreen when it is installed. To do this we require a network share setting up on a server that is onsite. The folder created will need to be directly shared out, so the backup will be something like (\\Server01\Inventrybackup$). Please could an ‘InVentry’ active directory username and password (a service account) be created and then attached to the Share & Security permissions. Once the share has been created, please could you email over just the share path and username? We do not require the password to be emailed, but please could this be provided to the engineer on arrival at site.

PLEASE NOTE: Your system will be down whilst the upgrade is taking place. You will need to have alternative methods in place for signing in and out to ensure you have live records for fire evacuation purposes until the works are complete. We recommend using a paper list to record Visitor, Staff and Pupil Sign In's/ Out's.

Your InVentry Training



Following the completion of your physical installation our engineer will conduct your introductory training session, approximately 30 minutes in length. This will only take place if social distancing (2-metre distance) can be adhered to throughout.



To receive the best possible training, we recommend it takes place in a room with a projector or electronic screen so your onsite staff can be trained safely and with good visibility. Alternatively, training can take place around your newly installed InVentry screen or onsite staff computers.



Following on from your introductory training, our training team will conduct a post installation training session which will be carried out via remote webinar. If our engineer is unable to complete your introductory training session on the day of installation, this training will be covered within the webinar, so no information will be missed.



If you’d like to book your post installation training webinar now, you can do so by using the following link:

https://training.inventry.co.uk/



Upon arrival, the engineer will discuss with you the best approach to complete training. This conversation will happen immediately so the necessary arrangements can be made for the training to take place safely.



Due to having to carry heavy tools and equipment, we kindly ask if our engineer can park within your onsite car park. If this is not possible, please could you advise on nearby parking facilities that our engineer can use.



Your InVentry equipment is going to be shipped directly to your site before your installation. It will be directed to the address discussed and confirmed during the implementation phase - this will be marked for your attention. The package will be shipped in a large, reinforced cardboard box, which will be clearly labelled with ‘InVentry’. This box should only be opened by your InVentry engineer, otherwise it could void the warranty of your InVentry equipment. The package will need to be signed for and safely retained within your organisation, ready for our installation engineer. If you would like the InVentry equipment to be shipped to a different location or to a different person, please can you let me by return email as soon as possible.



Should you have any queries please do not hesitate to get in contact.

Kind regards

Chloe Ellis
Scheduler

Hi Andrew,

As per our conversation earlier

There are different types of registration that need to be taken into account when creating accounts for students at each school.

Single Registration - This should create the account for a student as the student is registered only with this school
Dual Registration Main - This should create the account for this student as the student is registered with this school but could also be registered at another school in the area
Dual Registration Subsidiary - This should create the account for the student as they are registered with this school and although they may not attend all of their lessons at the school, they will need an account to access the school resources.
Guest Pupil - This does not normally need to create an account for the student. This scenario is likely to be the case if a student is attending a collaborative course at the school, but is not taking exams or registering on the AM/PM official register there or if the school is not receiving funding for this student

I understand that if a student is moving on a managed move between Trust school's this could cause a problem with the moving of the child's data between the schools, but a student cannot be without access to school systems and so if a second account needs to be created for this child with a different domain then this may need to be the case.

The litmus test for this would be if a student on a moved from our school to the school of a different trust on a managed move, there would be no delay in this student's account been created at the other school. We should follow the same process. A student must not be disadvantaged just because the managed move is within the same Trust

I hope this helps with your conversation that needs to be had with Vital

Kind Regards,

Mark Ward

Kat

Subject: P27 PCs Managed Service

Hi Jonathan

Our numbers for A Level Music Tech have been steadily increasing (brilliant!) but we've recruited 16 for Sept 23 - this is likely to be 17 now that an external student wants to switch from Music to Music Tech, with Music now not running in 23.

Great stuff for MT but our teaching space in P27/the studio only has 12 PCs in it - 11 student and 1 teacher. Although regular Music classroom P23 has 20 student PCs, timetabling always has MT on against GCSE or KS3 Music which means that P23 is just about always needed by other classes. The solution would be squeezing more PCs into P27 - we think 5 machines would cover us.

James came up to scope the space yesterday and we checked network ports and power points - both of which we seem to have plenty spare. James couldn't see a problem on those fronts. Space is the main issue so we are trailing some mini musical keyboards that are only as wide as a PC monitor screen (the existing keyboards are twice as wide and cause the space issue). Furnishing all PCs with these would allow us to squeeze in the 5 extra machines - we already have plenty of stools in there and luckily no legs on the desks to restrict seating.

James mentioned us possibly being able to get these extra PCs through the managed service, meaning no cost to the Music dept. We'd obviously cover the costs of music keyboards/audio interfaces/extra software licenses. The biggest need for this is the huge class of 17 we'll have in Y12 from September - we wouldn't be able to teach them in the existing space and don't have an alternative room - it'd be a mess for them. In a perfect world, we'd be able to have 2 groups of 8 but school can't afford that. Recruitment for MT does get stronger each year and the 2 GCSE groups of 2022-24 and secured 2 GCSE groups of 2023-25 will likely result in similar numbers for future MT cohorts. The extra PCs would not be left dormant after 2024. KS4 and 5 students often use P27 in study periods/P6 etc for coursework so the extra machines would help with that also.

Looking into future recruitment, we'll have to ensure a maximum number for the MT course as there is no more room for expansion - we'd have to cap it at 16 in future if we have these extra machines.

How does all of this sound?

Thanks
Ian

Hi,

I have been asked by the Head of Centre to liaise with Craig regarding the
email we sent about exam laptops


*As you are aware, we have a number of students who require the use of a
Word Processor for their exams.  Currently, this number stands at 16 and
could potentially rise over the next year.  Exams only have 7 laptops, one
of which is used in the Sports Hall to display the Exam Clock.
Additionally, these laptops are over 6 years old and are very slow, with
connectivity being one of the main issues.  Laptops take a long time to
load and can often crash.*

*Currently, we seat Word Processor students in their normal exam room with
access to a laptop.  This reduces the number of rooms being used and
therefore the number of staff we require.  *

*Back in 2020 we were bought around 15 additional laptops which were then
taken from us and distributed elsewhere.  Since then we have had a huge
reduction in IT Suites which has made arranging on-screen exams more
difficult.*

*Please can we request a set of laptops exclusively for exams use, i.e.
Word Processors, On-Screen Exams, Controlled Assessments, which will be
kept in the exams office and only used for exam purposes.  Obviously we
would not be able to allow these for general use, as they would need to
have the Exam Build installed and kept free from any damage or misuse.*

*The laptops don't need to be "all singing, all dancing" as they will only
be used for typing/research.  They do, however, need to be windows machines
as they need to have access to MS Word and we need the ability to disable
internet access through Impero.*

*Ideally, we would benefit from a class set (30-32) laptops in a trolley as
these can then be used for classes completing controlled assessments,
without the need to re-room classes timetabled to IT Suites.  With the
addition of Computer Science to the curriculum for the next academic year,
this will also be less disruptive to lessons that require access to IT.*

*If this is not possible, we are looking at needing 15 as a minimum for the
Summer Exams.*

*Nicola*

*Exams Officer*
*ASA*
